[Student "S"]
{South is to play 6\H. West leads the \SA, then \SK.

When you looked at just your and dummy's cards on the previous page it may have looked impossible to find a twelfth winner.

Even looking at all four hands here it is still very difficult to come up with a plan.

Here's a hint: If West holds 3 \Cs, (and you see that he does), can you squeeze him in \Cs and \Ss? 

Of course you ruffed the \SK.

The big problem with trying to squeeze West in the black suits right now is that East actually holds a \S guard. But you can fix that.

Play dummy's \HQ and \H10, then ruff a \S, then pull the last trump.  

Now play the \DA, \DK, and \DQ, discarding the \C3 from your hand.

Then lead dummy's \C7 to your \CK. 

[showcards N:ST,CA,C9 E:DJ,D9,CJ S:HA,C8,C6 W:SJ,CQ,CT]

Here you are in your hand.

Only West can guard dummy's \ST, and only West can guard dummy's\C9.

So you play your \HA and West must give up one of his guards. If he holds on to the \SJ then you toss dummy's useless \ST. If he throws the \SJ then you toss dummy's \C9.}
[Play "W"]SA

