[Student "S"]
{South is to play 3NT. West leads the \S3. East plays the \S5.

From the opening lead of \S3 and East's play of \S5 you should have deduced that West held five \Ss to the A K. Therefore if you lose a trick in any other suit West will be able to take 4 \S tricks and defeat you.

You have 8 winners, and if East holds 4+ \Hs AND 3+ \Ds then only he can guard the two suits.

But how can you squeeze him? 

The answer to that question is that <b>YOU</b> cannot squeeze him.

But maybe you can make his partner do the job for you.

At trick 2 you play a \S. 

Of course West will win this with his \SK.

And he will no doubt continue with the \SA and \S9.

You discard 2 \Ds from dummy and a \C from your hand.

East cannot spare either a \H or a \D so he also throws a \C. 

***Remember this position***

West will almost surely cash his \S2.

You and dummy both discard a \C and East also must discard a \C.

It doesn't matter what West plays next, lets say it is a \C. 

In your hand with the \CK, you now play the \CA.

East is truly squeezed. If he discards a \H, dummy's \H5 will become a winner. but if he discards a \D then you will get a third \D trick and the contract.

Since it was West who started the squeeze by cashing his last \S, this is called a Suicide Squeeze.<b>BUT</b>, what if West had not cashed that \S? 

***Here is the position you were supposed to remember***

Suppose West is a really expert defender and avoids the Suicide Squeeze by just refusing to cash his winning \S. It doesn't matter what else he plays instead, so let us assume it is a \C.

You win in your hand and establish a \D winner by playing \DA, \DK, and a small \D. East wins but cannot reach his partner's hand for that good \S.

So you establish a \D winner and make your contract.}
[Play "W"]S3

